@LAZY ANNOTATION
================

- Bean is created only when needed.
- Delays bean initialization.
- Improves startup performance.

Without @Lazy
-------------
Bean created during application startup.

With @Lazy
----------
Bean created only when first used.


Example
=======

@Component
@Lazy
class Engine {

    public Engine() {
        System.out.println("Engine Bean Created");
    }
}

@Component
class Car {

    @Autowired
    private Engine engine;
}


IMPORTANT POINTS
================
- Used for lazy initialization.
- Can be applied on:
  -> Class
  -> @Bean method
  -> Injection point
- Useful when bean creation is costly.
- Helps in circular dependency handling sometimes.


CIRCULAR / CYCLIC DEPENDENCY
============================

- Happens when two beans depend on each other.

Example:
A depends on B
B depends on A

This creates a cycle.


Example
=======

@Component
class A {

    @Autowired
    private B b;
}

@Component
class B {

    @Autowired
    private A a;
}


RESULT
======
- Spring may throw:
  BeanCurrentlyInCreationException


HOW TO RESOLVE
==============

1) Use @Lazy
------------

@Component
class A {

    @Autowired
    @Lazy
    private B b;
}

2) Use Setter Injection
-----------------------

@Component
class A {

    private B b;

    @Autowired
    public void setB(B b) {
        this.b = b;
    }
}

3) Redesign Application
-----------------------
- Best solution.
- Remove tight coupling between classes.


IMPORTANT POINTS
================
- Constructor Injection + Circular Dependency
  -> Not supported directly by Spring.

- Field/Setter Injection
  -> Can work using @Lazy.

- Circular dependency is considered bad design.

