Interceptor vs Filters:

FILTER vs INTERCEPTOR
=====================

FILTER
======
- Part of Servlet API.
- Works before request reaches DispatcherServlet.
- Used for:
  -> Authentication
  -> Logging
  -> CORS
  -> Request/Response modification

INTERCEPTOR
===========
- Part of Spring MVC.
- Works after DispatcherServlet and before Controller.
- Used for:
  -> Authentication
  -> Authorization
  -> Logging
  -> Handler processing


FILTER FLOW
============
Client
  ->
Filter
  ->
DispatcherServlet
  ->
Controller


INTERCEPTOR FLOW
================
Client
  ->
DispatcherServlet
  ->
Interceptor
  ->
Controller


FILTER METHODS
==============

1) init()
---------
- Called once when filter created.

2) doFilter()
-------------
- Main filtering logic.
- Executes for every request.

3) destroy()
------------
- Called when filter destroyed.


FILTER EXAMPLE
==============

@Component
public class MyFilter implements Filter {

    @Override
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest request,
                         ServletResponse response,
                         FilterChain chain)
                         throws IOException, ServletException {

        System.out.println("Before Request");

        chain.doFilter(request, response);

        System.out.println("After Response");
    }
}


INTERCEPTOR METHODS
===================

1) preHandle()
--------------
- Executes before Controller method.
- Return true -> continue request.
- Return false -> stop request.

2) postHandle()
---------------
- Executes after Controller method.
- Executes before response sent to client.

3) afterCompletion()
--------------------
- Executes after complete request and response.


INTERCEPTOR FLOW
================

preHandle()
    ->
Controller
    ->
postHandle()
    ->
afterCompletion()


INTERCEPTOR EXAMPLE
===================

@Component
public class MyInterceptor implements HandlerInterceptor {

    @Override
    public boolean preHandle(HttpServletRequest request,
                             HttpServletResponse response,
                             Object handler) {

        System.out.println("Before Controller");

        return true;
    }

    @Override
    public void postHandle(HttpServletRequest request,
                           HttpServletResponse response,
                           Object handler,
                           ModelAndView modelAndView) {

        System.out.println("After Controller");
    }

    @Override
    public void afterCompletion(HttpServletRequest request,
                                 HttpServletResponse response,
                                 Object handler,
                                 Exception ex) {

        System.out.println("Request Completed");
    }
}


MAIN DIFFERENCE
===============

FILTER
------
- Servlet level
- Works before DispatcherServlet
- Can modify request/response

INTERCEPTOR
-----------
- Spring MVC level
- Works before Controller
- Cannot easily modify request/response


WHEN TO USE
===========

Use Filter
-----------
- JWT validation
- CORS
- Compression
- Encoding

Use Interceptor
---------------
- Logging
- Authentication
- Authorization
- Execution timing

